com.siperian.sif.message.mrm

Class UnmergeRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.siperian.sif.message.SiperianRequest
      • com.siperian.sif.message.SiperianObjectRequest
        • com.siperian.sif.message.mrm.UnmergeRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    SiperianObjectUidProvider, SystemProvider, Serializable

    public class UnmergeRequest
extends SiperianObjectRequest
implements SystemProvider
    Unmerges base object (BO) records. A specific cross reference record is identified to unmerge from the BO.

    A base object record is a consolidated "best version of truth" (BVT) view of a collection of cross-reference records. Initially, a base object record has a single associated cross-reference record. Through merge, put, and cleansePut operations a base object record can acquire additional cross-reference records (see MergeRequest, PutRequest, and CleansePutRequest). When it is determined that a decision to consolidate separate BO records or cross references was invalid, Unmerge can be used to reverse it and separate the specific components contributing to the BVT view of the specified BO record.

    Required Parameters:

    • SiperianObjectUid - package or base object containing the records to unmerge. The primary table of the package must be a base object.
    • setXrefKey(XrefKey) - Identifies the cross-reference record to unmerge. XrefKey is a combination of sourceKey and systemName. A cross-reference record is always associated with a base object.
    • setTreeUnmerge(boolean) - Determines whether this will be a linear or tree unmerge operation, as described below.

    A simple scenario can illustrate the different styles of unmerge. Initially there are three base object records with ROWID_OBJECT of 1, 2, and 3. Each BO has a single cross-reference record with corresponding source keys of 1, 2, and 3 and systemName of SALES.

    Two merge operations are performed: 3 is merged into 2, then 2 is merged into 1. This leaves a single base object record with ROWID_OBJECT = 1 and three cross-reference records.

    Now we will unmerge sourceKey=2 and systemName=SALES. The following sections describe what happens with linear and tree unmerges.

    Linear Unmerge

    No attention is paid to the process by which the records were originally merged. The cross-reference for sourceKey 2 is removed from the base object and the base object record for sourceKey 2 is reinstated. The resulting base object records are as follows:

    • ROWID_OBJECT=1 has one cross-reference record with sourceKey 1.
    • ROWID_OBJECT=2 has two cross-reference records with sourceKeys 2 and 3.

    Tree Unmerge

    The process by which the records were originally merged determines the outcome. At the time record 2 was merged into record 1, record 3 had already been merged into 2. So the cross-references for sourceKeys 2 and 3 are removed from the base object and the base object record for sourceKey 2 is reinstated. The resulting base object records are as follows:

    • ROWID_OBJECT=1 has one cross-reference record with sourceKey 1.
    • ROWID_OBJECT=2 has two cross-reference records with sourceKeys 2 and 3.

    Note that in both cases, the consolidated field values in the base object record are recalculated after the unmerge.

    Cross-reference Added Directly to a Base Object

    Typically when a new cross-reference is inserted, a new base object record is created for it. But Put or CleansePut APIs and the "Load By ROWID" bath job can also add a cross-reference record directly to a base object. This means that the cross-reference record was never the only cross-reference for a base object record. When such a cross-reference record is identified to be unmerged it is deleted from the system - there is no independent base object record to reinstate for it.

    Cascade Unmerge

    Unmerge performs a cascade unmerge if this feature is enabled for this base object in the Schema Manager in the Hub Console. With cascade unmerge, when records in the parent object are unmerged, Siperian Hub also unmerges affected records in the child base object.

    Usage Example:

    The following example merges a record with ROWID_OBJECT = 782 into a record with ROWID_OBJECT = 123 using the package ADDRESS_UPDATE:

    UnmergeRequest request = new UnmergeRequest();
    request.setSiperianObjectUid("PACKAGE.ADDRESS_UPDATE");
    XrefKey xrefKey = new XrefKey();
    xrefKey.setSourceKey("782");
    xrefKey.setSystemName("SALES");
    request.setXrefKey(xrefKey);
    request.setTreeUnmerge(false);
    UnmergeResponse response = (UnmergeResponse) sipClient.process(request);

    Transaction Support

    When executed within an EJB context, this request can be part of a transaction with other requests. If there is a failure in any of the requests within a transaction, the entire transaction is rolled back.
